  pages={1-6},
  abstract={The current transformation of the energy system brings new challenges in the areas of supply security, reliability, and efficiency. Especially the decentralization leads to an increasing complexity and a bidirectional power flow. This requires an expansion and initiative-taking operation of the distribution grid. To investigate the behavior of a complex and dynamic distribution grid or individual plants within it, novel methods such as digital twins can be used. In this approach, a model is developed based on the real distribution grid, which can represent and predict the behavior of the real system. For this, the measurement of data in the physical distribution grid and the transmission of this data to the digital model is essential. This paper focuses on the development of a grid analyzer for digital twins of distribution grids. With the grid analyzer, the characteristics of the power grid like frequency or amplitude of voltage and current can be analyzed, evaluated, and finally sent to the digital twin. Functions such as a Fast Fourier Transformation, a Frequency- and Phase-Locked-Loop, and other algorithms are being developed to analyze the grid state. The development of the functions is model-based and follows different development stages from classic simulation over hybrid simulation to a laboratory test in the last chapter of the paper.},
