  pages={49-56},
  abstract={RSSI fingerprint-based localization has been one of the most attractive solutions, since it is free of extra infrastructure and specialized hardware. As wireless networks become more widely used, however, the number of APs for localization has been increasing and then results in "invalid APs", nearly APs that are redundant or have a negative impact on locating, and raises the computational overhead in the process of localization. To solve these problems, the previous literatures focused on selecting some efficient APs for localization. These approaches could remove a few of redundant APs and reduce the localization overhead to a certain extent, but the performance of locating will fluctuate significantly. In this paper, we propose a constructing efficient set of APs via spatial discrimination and localization difference, ESAP. First, for a single AP, we use the information gain rate to evaluate its spatial resolution ability, which effectively reflects the difference between the maps constructed by the fingerprints of each AP at different sampling points, and shows the AP’s discrimination of spatial locations. Moreover, we calculate the localization capability of APs at different sampling points, and design an incremental clustering algorithm based on the information gain rate of APs by using the localization differences of each AP at each sampling point. The algorithm generates various candidate sets according to the geographical diversity of AP’s fingerprint map, and is more robust in actual applications. Finally, an effective set of APs algorithm based on the minimum-maximum principle is proposed. In the process of constructing the effective set, suitable APs are chosen on the basis of the clustering results and the predefined requirements. Extensive experiments in real large-scale environment validates that the performance of our ESAP outperforms the existing AP selection methods, Info-Gain, ESC and SDN. When reducing APs by 40%, the accuracy of ESAP is better than these three methods by 15.5%, 22.2% and 10.11% respectively. Under different sampling densities, it can also maintain a good localization improvement effect. Meanwhile, our ESAP has better stability with 95% localization error within 1.3m.},
